04702nam a2200613Ia 9781501711466DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20182000nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017114667 a10.7591/97815017114662doi  a(DE-B1597)503363  a(OCoLC)1038487443  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHG1080.2.W66 1999 7aPOL0230002bisacsh04a332.4/9471 aWoodruff, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMoney Unmade :bBarter and the Fate of Russian Capitalism /cDavid Woodruff. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b6 drawings, 5 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tPreface -- tNote on Transliteration -- tINTRODUCTION. Making Money -- tCHAPTER ONE. Making Money Multiple, 1924-1933 -- tCHAPTER TWO. Things Come Apart, 1987-1991 -- tCHAPTER THREE. Bender's Revenge, 1992-1993 -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Money Unmade, 1993-1994 -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Monies Multiply, 1994-1996 -- tCHAPTER SIX. The Politics of Monetary Consolidation, 1996-1998 -- tEPILOGUE. Russian Monetary Consolidation in Comparative Perspective -- tAPPENDIX I. Internet Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the collapse of the Soviet Union, Russians have seen the ruble steadily lose ground to alternative means of payment such as barter and privately issued quasi-monies. Industry now collects as much as 70 percent of its receipts in nonmonetary form, leaving many firms with too little cash to pay salaries and taxes. In this ground-breaking book on the Russian economy, David Woodruff argues that Moscow's inability to control the nation's currency is not a carry-over from the Soviet past. Rather, the Russian government has failed to build the administrative capacity and political support demanded by monetary consolidation—a neglected but crucial aspect of capitalist statebuilding. Drawing on a vast array of empirical evidence, Woodruff shows how the widespread use of barter arose as local authorities tried to protect industry against the destructive effects of price increases and crude tax and accounting systems. As businesses fled or were driven from the money economy, provincial governments invented new ways to tax in kind and issued substitutes for the ruble. In turn, the federal authorities, unable to coerce firms either to operate in the money economy or to abandon business altogether, were forced to make accommodations to barter and to ruble alternatives. Woodruff describes the enormous fiscal difficulties that resulted and recounts the intense political battles over attempts to address the problem. Through an overview of monetary consolidation in other nations, Woodruff demonstrates that the struggles of the new Russian state have much to teach us about the political history of money worldwide. Sovereignty over money cannot, he argues, be imposed by government on a recalcitrant society. Nor can it be assumed as a by-product of disciplined policies aimed at market reform. Monetary consolidation is, at heart, a political achievement requiring political support.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aGeneral Economics. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171146640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501711466423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501711466/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EB